%N A098378 Number of characters needed to write number n in the traditional Ethiopic (Geez) number system.
%C A098378 These characters are visible with Mozilla 6 and IE 6, using the "TITUS Cyberbit Basic" font. Zooming in helps to differentiate the characters from each other.
%C A098378 The Ethiopic number system uses the following characters:
%C A098378 &#4969;=1 &#4970;=2 &#4971;=3 &#4972;=4 &#4973;=5 &#4974;=6 &#4975;=7 &#4976;=8 &#4977;=9
%C A098378 &#4978;=10 &#4979;=20 &#4980;=30 &#4981;=40 &#4982;=50 &#4983;=60 &#4984;=70 &#4985;=80 &#4986;=90
%C A098378 &#4987;=100 &#4988;=10000
%C A098378 A number is denoted by a sequence of powers of 100, each preceded by a coefficient (2 through 99). In each term of the series, the power 100^n is indicated by n &#4987; characters (merged to a digraph &#4988; when n=2). The coefficient is indicated by a tens digit and a ones digit, either of which is absent if its value is zero.
%D A098378 G. Haile, Ethiopic Writing, in The World's Writing Systems, edited by Peter T. Daniels & William Bright, Oxford Univ. Press, 1996. p. 574.
%H A098378 <a href="http://titus.fkidg1.uni-frankfurt.de/unicode/tituut.asp">TITUS Cyberbit Basic font</a>
%H A098378 Unicode Consortium, <a href="http://www.unicode.org/versions/Unicode4.0.0/ch12.pdf">Unicode Standard Version 4.0, Chapter 12, Additional Modern Scripts, Ethiopic</a>
%H A098378 Unicode Consortium, <a href="http://www.unicode.org/">Unicode Home Page</a> (Follow the link "Display Problems?" to find an appropriate information/font file to show the Ethiopic characters correctly).
%e A098378 E.g. the number 2345 is represented as (20+3)*100 + (40+5) = 20 3 100 40 5 = &#4979;&#4971;&#4987;&#4981;&#4973;, thus a(2345)=5. Also a(999)=4 (&#4977;&#4987;&#4986;&#4977), a(1000)=2 (&#4978;&#4987), a(9999)=5 (&#4986;&#4977;&#4987;&#4986;&#4977;), a(10000)=1 (&#4988;), a(1000000)=3 (&#4987;&#4987;&#4987;).
%Y A098378 Differs from A055640 first time at position n=200 (&#4970; &#4987; ) with a(200)=2, while A055640(200)=1, as only one nonzero arabic digit (and only one Greek letter) is needed for two hundred.
